Zero-downtime PHP-FPM Config change Steps and Actions :
—------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Important Reality (before we start)
Switching:
dynamic → static
means:
all 24 workers are created immediately on start
restart timing matters
bad restart = brief downtime
So we must reload gracefully, not restart blindly.


Niw Let’s do this process step by Step : 
—------------------------------------------------------

Step 1 — Locate PHP-FPM config : 


Depends on your PHP version. So know the PHP version by executing this command.
ps aux | grep php-fpm
Then after the command execution You’ll see something like:
php-fpm: master process (/etc/php/8.1/fpm/php-fpm.conf)



Common paths:
/etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf
/etc/php/7.4/fpm/pool.d/www.conf
Your changes go in pool config, not global config.



Step 2 – Take backup of the old Config details (This is MANDATORY Process) : 

sudo cp /etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf /etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf.bak





Step 3 — Now Edit configuration file by using this command: 


sudo nano /etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf






Then Update these values:


; PROCESS MANAGER
pm = static
pm.max_children = 24

; COMMENT these (not used in static mode, but still im adding these parameter, incase if we decided to switch into dynamic mode)
; pm.start_servers
; pm.min_spare_servers
; pm.max_spare_servers

; LIFECYCLE
pm.max_requests = 300

; MEMORY
php_admin_value[memory_limit] = 1480M


Important:
Always Use php_admin_value inside pool config (This will overrides php.ini safely)





Step 4 — Validate config (CRITICAL) : 
—--------------------------------------------------
Never skip this Steps.

sudo php-fpm8.1 -t
(or)

sudo php-fpm -t

Expected result is :
configuration file ... test is successful

If error → DO NOT reload



Step 5 — Graceful reload (ZERO downtime)


sudo systemctl reload php8.1-fpm

NOT restart the process, 
Just Use reload

Let’s see What reload does Really :
keeps old workers running
spins up new workers with new config
transitions smoothly
No dropped requests

If reload not supported (This is rare Scenario, but still, if reload, didn’t happened, use this command)
Fallback:
sudo service php8.1-fpm reload



Step 6 — Verify new config is active : 


1. Check process count : 


ps -ylC php-fpm --sort:rss

You should see the result like :


~24 worker processes
all active (static mode)

2. Count workers : 


ps aux | grep php-fpm | grep -v grep | wc -l



Expected Result after execute this COmmand :


1 master + 24 workers ≈ 25 processes




3. Check memory per worker : 


ps -o pid,rss,cmd -C php-fpm --sort=-rss | head

Confirm:
not all instantly huge
memory grows per request (normal)


4. Now Confirm Whether the config loaded is Loaded or Not By using this command : 


grep pm /etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf

5. Then Finely Check logs : 


sudo tail -f /var/log/php8.1-fpm.log
Look for:
errors 
worker spawn messages 


Step 7 — Live traffic validation (VERY IMPORTANT) : 


Immediately after deployed, The New Configuration :

First Watch CPU + memory Status : 


Htop


Check:
RAM usage stable (< 26GB)
no sudden spikes



Then Watch request handling : 


netstat -anp | grep php
|
or if behind nginx:
tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log

Ensure:
no spike in 5xx errors


Now Check queueing Status : 

If nginx:
tail -f /var/log/nginx/error.log

Look for:
upstream timed out
connection refused





Step 8 — Post-deploy observation (THIS is where most fail) : 
Watch for 30–60 mins:

Warning signs:
memory creeping up continuously
workers stuck at high RSS
increasing response time

What changes after static mode?
Before (dynamic):
workers scale
safer for memory bursts
After (static):
fixed 24 workers
predictable memory
less flexible under spikes




Risk you must monitor : 
If:
6–8 workers become heavy (1.3GB)
remaining workers handle all traffic

You may see:
queueing
latency increase

This was Optional (but STRONGLY recommended) : 

Add safety Config, PHP Config :
request_terminate_timeout = 300s
Then reload again.

Rollback plan (if anything goes wrong) : 


sudo cp /etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf.bak /etc/php/8.1/fpm/pool.d/www.conf
—-------------

sudo systemctl reload php8.1-fpm
This takes Back to previous config instantly…..

